            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Thanks for the issue!\n\nYes indeed, I can reproduce. When installing from the lockfile, the whole specification [is constructed manually from the lockfile](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/1a02896e169b7e22c489dd5b7f60b570c496631e/runtime/lua/vim/pack.lua#L888-L889).\n\nI think it is reasonable for it to include `data` from the `vim.pack.add()` call, at least for this (valid) use case. The small problem here is what to do with other fields (since they theoretically be in conflict): should they still be reconstructed from the lockfile or prefer `vim.pack.add()` data? My initial thought is the former since it is what is used during installation.\n\nI'll take a look soon-ish (hopefully within a day or two).\n\n---\n\nFor reference, a simpler reproduction steps:\n\n1. Create the following 'init.lua':\n\n    ```lua\n    _G.log = {}\n    vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd(\n      { 'PackChangedPre', 'PackChanged' },\n      { callback = function(ev) table.insert(_G.log, { event = ev.event, spec = ev.data.spec }) end }\n    )\n    vim.pack.add({\n      { src = 'https://github.com/nvim-mini/mini.ai', data = true },\n    })\n    ```\n2. With clean state, run `NVIM_APPNAME=nvim-repro nvim` and install the plugin. Executing `:=log` shows that `data = true` is present.\n3. From shell do `rm -r ~/.local/share/nvim-repro/site/pack/core/opt/mini.ai/` to imitate install with lockfile.\n4. Again run `NVIM_APPNAME=nvim-repro nvim` and install the plugin. Executing `:=log` shows that `data = true` is absent.",
